label.value: antennal mechanosensory and motor center AMMC Db6 neuron

value.value: Descending bilateral neuron whose large cell body is located in the cell body rind on the ventral region of the gnathal ganglion. The primary neurite extends dorsally to broadly form postsynaptic terminals bilaterally in the gnathal ganglion and flange. The neurite further extends laterally to arborize bilaterally in the antennal mechanosensory and motor center (AMMC) zone A and saddle. A contralateral neurite in the gnathal ganglion exits the brain, projecting into the thoracic-abdominal ganglion. Postsynaptic terminals are also found in the ipsilateral AMMC zone A.

definition.value: The location of presynaptic terminals could not be determined (Matsuo et al., 2016).

value.value: The most medial slice of the protocerebral bridge of the adult brain. It is the smallest of the slices.

definition.value: The identification of this slice by Wolff et al. (2015) meant that the domain that was previously called slice 1 corresponds in fact to slice 2. Author mentions of 8 slices in the protocerebral bridge indicates that they are using the old nomenclature.

label.value: protocerebral bridge 1 glomerulus-fan-shaped body-nodulus 2 ventral domain neuron

value.value: Small field neuron of the central complex with dendritic arbors in a single glomerulus of the protocerebral bridge, presynaptic terminals in fan-shaped body layer 3 and mixed terminals in the ventral domain of contralateral nodulus 2 (Wolff et al., 2015; Hulse et al., 2021). These cells collectively target protocerebral bridge glomeruli 2-9 (Wolff et al., 2015; Hulse et al., 2021). There are approximately 20 cells of this type per organism (Hulse et al., 2021). They encode contralateral backwards translational motion (Lu et al., 2022).

definition.value: Hulse et al. (2021) do not divide PFNv into subtypes.

label.value: protocerebral bridge 1 glomerulus-fan-shaped body-nodulus 3 medial domain neuron

value.value: Small field neuron of the central complex with dendritic arbors in a single glomerulus of the protocerebral bridge, presynaptic terminals in a tooth of fan-shaped body layer 1 and mixed terminals in the medial domain of contralateral nodulus 3 (Wolff et al., 2015; Hulse et al., 2021). These cells collectively target protocerebral bridge glomeruli 2-9 (Wolff et al., 2015; Hulse et al., 2021).

definition.value: Hulse et al. (2021) divide PFNm into two (a and b) subtypes, but it is not clear how these are different from each other or which cells correspond to the type in Wolff et al. (2015).

label.value: adult superior posterior slope-protocerebral bridge neuron

value.value: Interneuron that has dendritic arborizations in the ipsilateral superior posterior slope and sparse axon terminals in glomeruli 2-9 of the ipsilateral protocerebral bridge (Wolff et al., 2015). Occasionally, glomerulus 1 is also innervated and arbors may extend into the contralateral protocerebral bridge (Wolff et al., 2015). It develops from the PBp1 neuroblast (Kandimalla et al., 2023).
Neuron whose cell body lies in the cortex of the lobula. It arborizes in the anterior lobula, with a small bush-like display in layers 5 and 6.

Neuron whose cell body lies in the cortex of the lobula. It arborizes over a large area of the lobula, mostly in layer 5 but with some branches in layer 4. It receives very strong synaptic input from Tm5a/b/c and Tm20 neurons (Lin et al., 2016). There are approximately 30 of these cells per hemisphere (Lin et al., 2016).

definition.value: Connectivity data was assessed by GRASP and double-labeling EM (Lin et al., 2016).

value.value: Adult ascending neuron that is activated downstream of female pheromone-sensing neurons (Kallman et al., 2015). Its soma is located in the dorsal part of the cell body rind of the metathoracic neuromere (Kallman et al., 2015). It arborizes in all leg and wing neuropils and projects to the ventrolateral protocerebrum (Kallman et al., 2015). There is one of these cells per hemisphere (Kallman et al., 2015).

definition.value: Not fru+ or sexually dimorphic despite involvement in courtship behavior in the male (not tested in female) (Kallman et al., 2015).
